#: ../../theory/background.rst:2
msgid "Scientific Background"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:5
msgid "Electron Density and Density Functional Theory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:7
msgid "The electron density is one of the most fundamental physical quantities in condensed matter physics and materials science. According to the Hohenberg-Kohn theorem, the ground-state electron density uniquely determines all ground-state properties of a many-electron system, including the total energy, forces, stress tensor, and related observables."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:9
msgid "Traditionally, obtaining an accurate electron density distribution requires self-consistent field iterations within Kohn-Sham density functional theory (KSDFT). KSDFT obtains orbital wavefunctions by solving the single-particle Kohn-Sham equations, from which the electron density is constructed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:11
msgid "n(\\mathbf{r}) = \\sum_i f_i |\\psi_i(\\mathbf{r})|^2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:15
msgid "where :math:`\\psi_i` are the Kohn-Sham orbitals and :math:`f_i` are the corresponding occupation numbers. The computational complexity of this procedure scales steeply with system size, limiting its applicability to large-scale materials screening."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:18
msgid "Orbital-Free Density Functional Theory"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:20
msgid "Orbital-free density functional theory (Orbital-Free DFT, OFDFT) provides an alternative route that bypasses the Kohn-Sham equations entirely. Within the OFDFT framework, ground-state materials properties are expressed directly through the variational minimization of an energy functional of the electron density, without explicitly solving for orbital wavefunctions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:23
msgid "E(3) Equivariance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:25
msgid "The electron density of a physical system must satisfy the symmetry constraints of the three-dimensional Euclidean group E(3), remaining equivariant under rotations, translations, and inversion:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:27
msgid "**Translation equivariance**: A global translation of the atomic structure results in an identical translation of the electron density field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:28
msgid "**Rotation equivariance**: A rotation of the atomic structure induces the same rotation in the electron density field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:29
msgid "**Inversion equivariance**: Spatial inversion of the atomic structure produces a corresponding inversion of the electron density field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:31
msgid "Embedding E(3) equivariance as a hard constraint into the neural network architecture significantly improves data efficiency and generalization, ensuring that predicted electron densities are physically consistent by construction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:34
msgid "Message Passing Neural Networks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:36
msgid "Message passing neural networks (MPNNs), a class of graph neural networks (GNNs), are a natural framework for processing atomic structure data. Within the MPNN formalism:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:38
msgid "Atoms are represented as nodes of a graph, carrying features such as element type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:39
msgid "Chemical bonds or nearest-neighbor relationships between atoms are represented as edges of the graph."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:40
msgid "Through multiple rounds of message passing, each atom aggregates information from its neighbors, progressively building a representation of its local chemical environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../theory/background.rst:42
msgid "This mechanism is naturally suited to describing interatomic interactions in materials and can handle crystal structures of arbitrary size and composition."
msgstr ""
